Technical Explanation of Garmin Heart Rate Measurement

(Below is a condensed but equally technical translation)

1. Overview

Garmin’s Elevate™ Optical Heart Rate System combines:

Optical PPG sensors

Motion sensors (accelerometer + gyroscope)

Temperature sensors

A digital signal processor (DSP) and proprietary algorithms

It estimates HR (Heart Rate) and HRV (Heart Rate Variability) from light absorption changes in capillaries.

2. Photoplethysmography (PPG) Principle

Biophysics:

Each heartbeat increases blood volume in peripheral vessels → alters light absorption → measurable via reflected light intensity.Sensor Components:

LEDs (green/red/IR)

Photodiode receiver

Optical lens and window

Sampling rate: 25–200 Hz

Wavelength usage:

 

3. Signal Processing Pipeline

Preprocessing:

DC offset removal

Band-pass filtering (0.5–5 Hz)

Adaptive Gain Control

Motion artifact cancellation using accelerometer data

Peak Detection:

Derivative and threshold-based algorithms (Pan-Tompkins-like)

Identify periodic peaks corresponding to heartbeats

Heart Rate Computation:

HR=60IBIHR = \frac{60}{IBI}HR=IBI60 HRV Analysis:

FFT and time-domain metrics to assess autonomic balance (LF/HF ratio).

4. Role of Accelerometer and Gyroscope in the Heart Rate Measurement System

1. Accelerometer

Function: Detects motion and vibration, used for signal correction and activity recognition.

a. Motion Artifact Elimination

When the arm moves during running or cycling, significant vibrations occur, causing interference in the optical heart rate sensor’s (PPG) reflected light signal.

The accelerometer continuously detects these mechanical movements and compensates for them through algorithms, filtering out light intensity variations unrelated to the heartbeat, thereby improving the accuracy of heart rate readings.

b. Activity Recognition

The accelerometer identifies whether the user is walking, running, or stationary.

c. Adaptive Algorithm Adjustment and Cadence Analysis

Based on detected activity, the system automatically adjusts the sensitivity and sampling rate of the heart rate filtering algorithm—for instance, using high-precision sampling during rest and dynamic filtering during motion.

During exercise, the accelerometer can also synchronize with the heart rate signal to distinguish step cadence from pulse frequency, preventing confusion between the two.

2. Gyroscope

Function: Detects angular velocity and posture changes, assisting in PPG signal stabilization and orientation compensation.

a. Posture and Angle Compensation

When the wrist rotates or the watch angle changes, the incident and reflected light paths shift, causing deviations in the heart rate signal.

The gyroscope monitors these angular changes and adjusts the optical sampling model accordingly, maintaining stability in PPG signal processing.

b. Motion Differentiation

Together with the accelerometer, the gyroscope distinguishes between “micro skin movements caused by heartbeat” and “large-scale arm movements,” enhancing signal filtering accuracy.

c. Motion Type Recognition

The gyroscope also identifies complex motion types (such as swimming strokes, weightlifting, or cycling posture changes), allowing the system to dynamically adjust heart rate algorithm parameters.

3. Collaborative Working Principle

Garmin’s sensing algorithm employs multi-sensor fusion technology:

HR=f(PPG Signal,Accelerometer Data,Gyroscope Data)

The system integrates PPG, acceleration, and angular velocity signals through machine learning or adaptive filtering models to automatically recognize true pulse waveforms.

This enables the device to maintain stable and accurate heart rate output even during intense physical activity.

5. Error Sources and Mitigation

 

6. Chest Strap (ECG)

Measures heart’s electrical signal via skin electrodes

High accuracy (error < ±1 BPM)

Used for HIIT, cycling, and swimming

Transmits via ANT+ or BLE

 

7. Advanced Algorithm Fusion

Garmin integrates:

Multi-spectral PPG fusion

Activity-aware HR models

AI-based adaptive filtering

Signal Quality Index (SQI)

Seamless switching to chest strap or predictive modeling when optical quality degrades
